\par In a last-ditch attempt to cheer Ron up, Harry persuaded him to come along to the Gryffindor team\rquote s final practice before the Ravenclaw match, so that he could have a go on the Firebolt after they\rquote d finished. This did seem to take Ron
\rquote s mind off Scabbers for a moment (\lquote Brilliant! Can I try and shoot a few goals on it?\rquote ) so they set off for the Quidditch pitch together.
\par Madam Hooch, who was still overseeing Gryffindor practices to keep an eye on Harry, was just as impressed with the Firebolt as everyone else had been. She took it in her hands before take-off and gave them the benefit of her professional opinion.
\par \lquote Look at the balance on it! If the Nimbus series has a fault, it\rquote s a slight list to the tail-end \endash  you often find they develop a drag after a few years. They\rquote 
ve updated the handle, too, a bit slimmer than the Cleansweeps, reminds me of the old Silver Arrows \endash  a pity they\rquote ve stopped making them, I learnt to fly on one, and a very fine old broom it was too \'85\rquote 
\par She continued in this vein for some time, until Wood said, \lquote Er \endash  Madam Hooch? Is it OK if Harry has the Firebolt back? Only we need to practise ...\rquote 
\par \lquote Oh \endash  right \endash  here you are, then, Potter,\rquote  said Madam Hooch. \lquote I\rquote ll sit over here with Weasley ...\rquote 
\par She and Ron left the pitch to sit in the stadium, and the Gryffindor team gathered around Wood for his final instructions for tomorrow\rquote s match.
\par \lquote Harry, I\rquote ve just found out who Ravenclaw are playing as Seeker. It\rquote s Cho Chang. She\rquote s a fourth-year, and she\rquote s pretty good ... I really hoped she wouldn\rquote t be fit, she\rquote s had some problems with injuries ...
\rquote  Wood scowled his displeasure that Cho Chang had made a full recovery, then said, \lquote On the other hand, she rides a Comet Two Sixty, which is going to look like a joke next to the Firebolt.\rquote  He gave Harry\rquote 
s broom a look of fervent admiration, then said, \lquote OK, everyone, let\rquote s go \endash \rquote 
\par And at long last, Harry mounted his Firebolt, and kicked off from the ground.
\par It was better than he\rquote d ever dreamed. The Firebolt
 turned with the lightest touch; it seemed to obey his thoughts rather than his grip. It sped across the pitch at such speed that the stadium turned into a green and grey blur; Harry turned it so sharply that Alicia Spinnet screamed, then he went into a p
erfectly controlled dive, brushing the grassy pitch with his toes before rising thirty, forty, fifty feet into the air again \endash 
\par \lquote Harry, I\rquote m letting the Snitch out!\rquote  Wood called.
\par Harry turned and raced a Bludger towards the goalposts; he outstripped it easily, saw the Snitch dart out from behind Wood and within ten seconds had caught it tightly in his hand.
\par The team cheered madly. Harry let the Snitch go again, gave it a minute\rquote s head start, then tore after it, weaving in and out of the others; he spotted it lurking near Katie Bell\rquote s knee, looped her eas\-ily, and caught it again.
\par It was the best practice ever; the team, inspired by the presence of the Firebolt in their midst, performed their best moves fault\-lessly, and by the time they hit the ground again, Wood didn\rquote 
t have a single criticism to make, which, as George Weasley pointed out, was a first.
\par \lquote I can\rquote t see what\rquote s going to stop us tomorrow!\rquote  said Wood. \lquote Not unless \endash  Harry, you\rquote ve sorted your Dementor problem, haven\rquote t you?\rquote 
\par \lquote Yeah,\rquote  said Harry, thinking of his feeble Patronus and wishing it was stronger.
\par \lquote The Dementors won\rquote t turn up again, Oliver, Dumbledore\rquote d do his nut,\rquote  said Fred confidently.
\par \lquote Well, let\rquote s hope not,\rquote  said Wood. \lquote Anyway \endash  good work, every\-one. Let\rquote s get back to the Tower \endash  turn in early ...\rquote 
\par \lquote I\rquote m staying out for a bit, Ron wants a go on the Firebolt,\rquote  Harry told Wood, and while the rest of the team headed off to the chang\-ing rooms, Harry strode over to Ron, who
 vaulted the barrier to the stands and came to meet him. Madam Hooch had fallen asleep in her seat.
\par \lquote Here you go,\rquote  said Harry, handing Ron the Firebolt.
\par Ron, an expression of ecstasy on his face, mounted the broom and zoomed off into the gathering darkness
 while Harry walked around the edge of the pitch, watching him. Night had fallen before Madam Hooch awoke with a start, told Harry and Ron off for not waking her, and insisted that they go back to the castle.
\par Harry shouldered the Firebolt and he and Ron walked out of the shadowy stadium, discussing the Firebolt\rquote 
s superbly smooth action, its phenomenal acceleration and its pinpoint turning. They were halfway towards the castle when Harry, glancing to his left, saw something that made his heart turn over \endash  a pair of eyes, gleaming out of the darkness.

\par Harry stopped dead, his heart banging against his ribs.
\par \lquote What\rquote s the matter?\rquote  said Ron.
\par Harry pointed. Ron pulled out his wand and muttered, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196 \lquote Lumos!\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196 
\par A beam of light fell across the grass, hit the bottom of a tree and illuminated its branches; there, crouching amongst the bud\-ding leaves, was Crookshanks.
\par \lquote Get out of it!\rquote  Ron roared, and he stooped down and seized a stone lying on the grass, but before he could do anything else, Crookshanks had vanished with one swish of his long ginger tail.
\par \lquote See?\rquote  Ron said furiously, chucking the stone down again. \lquote She\rquote s still letting him wander about wherever he wants \endash  probably washing down Scabbers with a couple of birds now ...\rquote 
\par Harry didn\rquote t say anything. He took a deep breath as relief seeped through him; he had been sure for a moment that those eyes had belonged to the Grim. They set off for the castle once more. Slightly ashamed of his moment of panic, Harry didn
\rquote t say anything to Ron \endash  nor did he look left or right until they had reached the well lit Entrance Hall.
