Home Life and Social Habits of British Muggles. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196 Harry broke away from the table where Fred and George had started jug\-gling Butterbeer bottles, and went over to her.

\par \lquote Did you even come to the match?\rquote  he asked her.
\par \lquote Of course I did,\rquote  said Hermione, in a strangely high-pitched voice, not looking up. \lquote And I\rquote m very glad we won, and I think you did really well, but I need to read this by Monday.\rquote 
\par \lquote Come on, Hermione, come and have some food,\rquote  Harry said, looking over at Ron and wondering whether he was in a good enough mood to bury the hatchet.
\par \lquote I can\rquote t, Harry, I\rquote ve still got four hundred and twenty-two pages to read!\rquote  said Hermione, now sounding slightly hysterical. \lquote Anyway ...\rquote  she glanced over at Ron, too, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196 \lquote he}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196  doesn\rquote t want me to join in.\rquote 
\par There was no arguing with this, as Ron chose that moment to say loudly, \lquote If Scabbers hadn\rquote t just been }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196 eaten, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196 he could have had some of these Fudge Flies, he used to really like them \endash \rquote 
\par Hermione burst into tears. Before Harry could say or do any\-thing, she had tucked the enormous book under her arm, and, still sobbing, run towards the staircase to the girls\rquote  dormitories and out of sight.
\par \lquote Can\rquote t you give her a break?\rquote  Harry asked Ron quietly.
\par \lquote No,\rquote  said Ron flatly. \lquote If she just acted like she was sorry \endash  but she\rquote ll never admit she\rquote s wrong, Hermione. She\rquote s still acting like Scabbers has gone on holiday or something.\rquote 
\par The Gryffindor party only ended when Professor McGonagall
 turned up in her tartan dressing-gown and hair-net at one in the morning, to insist that they all went to bed. Harry and Ron climbed the stairs to their dormitory, still discussing the match. At last, exhausted, Harry climbed into bed, twitched the hangi
ngs of his four-poster shut to block out a ray of moonlight, lay back and felt himself almost instantly drifting off to sleep ...
\par He had a very strange dream. He was walking through a forest, his Firebolt over his shoulder, following something silvery white
. It was winding its way through the trees ahead, and he could only catch glimpses of it between the leaves. Anxious to catch up with it, he sped up, but as he moved faster, so did his quarry. Harry broke into a run and ahead, he heard hooves gathering sp
eed. Now he was running flat out, and ahead he could hear galloping. Then he turned a corner into a clearing and \endash 
\par \lquote AAAAAAAAAAAAAARRRRRRRRRRRRGGGHHHHH! NOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOOO!\rquote 
\par Harry woke as suddenly as though he\rquote d been hit in the face. Disorientated in the total darkness, he fumbled with his hangings \endash  he could hear movements around him, and Seamus Finnigan\rquote s voice from the other side of the room.
\par \lquote What\rquote s going on?\rquote 
\par Harry thought he heard the dormitory door slam. At last find\-ing the divide in his curtains, he ripped them back, and at the same moment, Dean Thomas lit his lamp.
\par Ron was sitting up in bed, the hangings torn from one side, a look of the utmost terror on his face.
\par \lquote Black! Sirius Black! With a knife!\rquote 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196 \lquote What?\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196 
\par \lquote Here! Just now! Slashed the curtains! Woke me up!\rquote 
\par \lquote You sure you weren\rquote t dreaming, Ron?\rquote  said Dean.
\par \lquote Look at the curtains! I tell you, he was here!\rquote 
\par They all scrambled out of bed; Harry reached the dormitory door first, and they sprinted back down the staircase. Doors opened behind them, and sleepy voices called after them.
\par \lquote Who shouted?\rquote 
\par \lquote What\rquote re you doing?\rquote 
\par The common room was lit by the glow of the dying fire, still lit\-tered with debris from the party. It was deserted.
\par \lquote Are you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196 sure}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196  you weren\rquote t dreaming, Ron?\rquote 
\par \lquote I\rquote m telling you, I saw him!\rquote 
\par \lquote What\rquote s all the noise?\rquote 
\par \lquote Professor McGonagall told us to go to bed!\rquote 
\par A few of the girls had come down their staircase, pulling on dressing-gowns and yawning. Boys, too, were reappearing.
