\par \lquote Maybe I was seeing things,\rquote  said Harry. \lquote But ... from what I could see ... it looked like him ... I\rquote ve got photos of him ...\rquote 
\par Hermione was still looking at him as though worried about his sanity.
\par \lquote I know it sounds mad,\rquote  said Harry flatly. He turned to look at Buckbeak, who was digging his beak into the ground, apparently searching for worms. But he wasn\rquote t really watching Buckbeak.
\par He was thinking about his father, and about his three oldest friends ... Moony, Wormtail, Padfoot and Prongs ... Had all four of them been out in the grounds tonight? Wormtail had reappeared this evening when everyone had thought he was dead \endash 
 was it so impossible his father had done the same? Had he been seeing things across the lake? The figure had been too far away to see distinctly ... yet he had felt sure, for a moment, before he\rquote d lost consciousness ...
\par The leaves overhead rustled faintly in the breeze. The moon drifted in and out of sight behind the shifting clouds. Hermione sat with her face turned towards the Willow, waiting.
\par And then, at last, after over an hour ...
\par \lquote Here we come!\rquote  Hermione whispered.
\par She and Harry got to their feet. Buckbeak raised his head. They saw Lupin, Ron and Pettigrew c
lambering awkwardly out of the hole in the roots, followed by the unconscious Snape, drifting weirdly upwards. Next came Harry, Hermione and Black. Next came Harry and Black. They all began to walk towards the castle.
\par Harry\rquote s heart was starting to beat very fast. He glanced up at the sky. Any moment now, that cloud was going to move aside and show the moon ...
\par \lquote Harry,\rquote  Hermione muttered, as though she knew exactly what he was thinking, \lquote we\rquote ve got to stay put. We mustn\rquote t be seen. There\rquote s nothing we can do ...\rquote 
\par \lquote So we\rquote re just going to let Pettigrew escape all over again ...\rquote  said Harry quietly.
\par \lquote How do you expect to find a rat in the dark?\rquote  snapped Hermione. \lquote There\rquote s nothing we can do! We came back to help Sirius. We\rquote re not supposed to be doing anything else!\rquote 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196 \lquote All right!\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196 
\par The moon slid out from behind its cloud. They saw the tiny figures across the grounds stop. Then they saw movement \endash 
\par \lquote There goes Lupin,\rquote  Hermione whispered. \lquote He\rquote s transforming \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote Hermione!\rquote  said Harry suddenly. \lquote We\rquote ve got to move!\rquote 
\par \lquote We mustn\rquote t, I keep telling you \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote Not to interfere! But Lupin\rquote s going to run into the Forest, right at us!\rquote 
\par Hermione gasped.
\par \lquote Quick!\rquote  she moaned, dashing to untie Buckbeak. \lquote Quick! Where are we going to go? Where are we going to hide? The Dementors will be coming any moment \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote Back to Hagrid\rquote s!\rquote  Harry said. \lquote It\rquote s empty now \endash  come on!\rquote 
\par They ran, fast as they could, Buckbeak cantering along behind them. They could hear the werewolf howling behind them ...
\par The cabin was in sight. Harry skidded to the door, wrenched it open and Hermione and Buckbeak flashed past him; Harry threw himself in after them and bolted the door. Fang the boarhound barked loudly.
\par \lquote Shh, Fang, it\rquote s us!\rquote  said Hermione, hurrying over and scratch\-ing his ears to quieten him. \lquote That was really close!\rquote  she said to Harry.
\par \lquote Yeah ...\rquote 
\par Harry was looking out of the window. It was much harder to see what was going on from here. Buckbeak seemed very happy to find himself back inside Hagrid\rquote s house. He lay down in front of the fire, folded his wings contentedl
y and seemed ready for a good nap.
\par \lquote I think I\rquote d better go outside again, you know,\rquote  said Harry slow\-ly. \lquote I can\rquote t see what\rquote s going on \endash  we won\rquote t know when it\rquote s time \endash \rquote 
\par Hermione looked up. Her expression was suspicious.
\par \lquote I\rquote m not going to try and interfere,\rquote  said Harry quickly. \lquote But if we don\rquote t see what\rquote s going on, how\rquote re we going to know when it\rquote s time to rescue Sirius?\rquote 
\par \lquote Well ... OK, then ... I\rquote ll wait here with Buckbeak ... but Harry, be careful \endash  there\rquote s a werewolf out there \endash  and the Dementors \endash \rquote 
\par Harry stepped outside again and edged around the cabin. He could hear yelping in the distance. That meant the Dementors were closing in on Sirius ... he and Hermione would be running to him any moment ...
\par Harry stared out towards the lake, his heart doing a kind of drum-roll in his chest. Whoever had sent that Patronus would be appearing at any moment.
\par For a fraction of a second he stood, irresolute, in front of Hagrid\rquote s door. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196 You must not be seen. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196 But he didn\rquote t want to be seen. He wanted to do the seeing ... he had to know ...
\par And there were the Dementors. They were emerging out of the darkness from every direction, gliding around the edges of the lake ... they were moving away from where Harry stood, to the opposite bank ... he wouldn\rquote t have to get near them ...
\par Harry began to run. He had no thought in his head except his father ... If it was him ... if it really was him ... he had to know, had to find out ...
\par The lake was coming nearer and nearer, but there was no sign of anybody. On the opposite bank, he could see tiny glimmers of silver \endash  his own attempts at a Patronus \endash 
\par There was a bush at the very edge of the water. Harry threw himself behind it, peering desperately through the leaves. On the opposite bank, the glimmers of silver were suddenly extinguished. A terrified excitement shot through him \endash 
 any moment now \endash 
\par \lquote Come on!\rquote  he muttered, staring about. \lquote Where are you? Dad, come on \endash \rquote 
\par But no one came. Harry raised his head to look at the circle of Dementors across the lake. One of them was lowering its hood. It was time for the rescuer to appear \endash  but no one was coming to help this time \endash 
\par And then it hit him \endash  he understood. He hadn\rquote t seen his father \endash  he had seen }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196 himself \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196 
\par Harry flung himself out from behind the bush and pulled out his wand.
\par \lquote EXPECTO PATRONUM!\rquote  he yelled.
\par And out of the end of his wand burst, not a shapeless cloud of mist, but a blinding, dazzling, silver animal. He screwed up his eyes, trying to see what it was. It looked like a horse. It was gal\-loping silently away from him, across the black 
surface of the lake. He saw it lower its head and charge at the swarming Dementors ... now it was galloping around and around the black shapes on the ground, and the Dementors were falling back, scat\-
tering, retreating into the darkness ... they were gone.
\par The Patronus turned. It was cantering back towards Harry across the still surface of the water. It wasn\rquote t a horse. It wasn\rquote t a unicorn, either. It was a stag. It was shining brightly as the moon above ... it was coming back to him ...
\par It stopped on the bank. Its hooves made no mark on the soft ground as it stared at Harry with its large, silver eyes. Slowly, it bowed its antlered head. And Harry realised ...
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196 \lquote Prongs,\rquote  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196 he whispered.
\par But as his trembling fingertips stretched towards the creature, it vanished.
\par Harry stood there, hand still outstretched. Then, with a great leap of his heart, he heard hooves behind him \endash  he whirled around and saw Hermione dashing towards him, dragging Buckbeak behind her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196 \lquote What did you do?\rquote  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196 she said fiercely. \lquote You said you were 
only going to keep a lookout!\rquote 
\par \lquote I just saved all our lives ...\rquote  said Harry. \lquote Get behind here \endash  behind this bush \endash  I\rquote ll explain.\rquote 
\par Hermione listened to what had just happened with her mouth open yet again.
\par \lquote Did anyone see you?\rquote 
\par \lquote Yes, haven\rquote t you been listening? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196 I}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196 
 saw me but I thought I was my dad! It\rquote s OK!\rquote 
\par \lquote Harry, I can\rquote t believe it \endash  you conjured up a Patronus that drove away all those Dementors! That\rquote s very, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196 very }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196 advanced magic ...\rquote 
\par \lquote I knew I could do it this time,\rquote  said Harry, \lquote because I\rquote d already done it ... Does that make sense?\rquote 
\par \lquote I don\rquote t know \endash  Harry, look at Snape!\rquote 
\par Together they peered around the bush at the other bank. Snape had regained consciousness. He was conjuring stretchers and lift\-ing the limp forms of Harry, Hermione and Black onto them. A f
ourth stretcher, no doubt bearing Ron, was already floating at his side. Then, wand held out in front of him, he moved them away towards the castle.
\par \lquote Right, it\rquote s nearly time,\rquote  said Hermione tensely, looking at her watch. \lquote We\rquote ve got about forty-five minutes until Dumbledore locks the door to the hospital wing. We\rquote 
ve got to rescue Sirius and get back into the ward before anybody realises we\rquote re missing ...\rquote 
\par They waited, watching the moving clouds reflected in the lake, while the bush next to them whispered in the breeze. Buckbeak, bored, was ferreting for worms again.
\par \lquote D\rquote you reckon he\rquote s up there yet?\rquote  said Harry, checking his watch. He looked up at the castle, and began counting the win\-dows to the right of the West Tower.
\par \lquote Look!\rquote  Hermione whispered. \lquote Who\rquote s that? Someone\rquote s coming back out of the castle!\rquote 
\par Harry stared through the darkness. The man was hurrying across the grounds, towards one of the entrances. Something shiny glinted in his belt.
\par \lquote Macnair!\rquote  said Harry. \lquote The executioner! He\rquote s gone to get the Dementors! This is it, Hermione \endash \rquote 
\par Hermione put her hands on Buckbeak\rquote s back and Harry gave her a leg up. Then he placed his foot on one of the lower branches of the bush and climbed up in front of her. He pulled Buckbeak\rquote s rope back over his neck and tied it to
 the other side of his collar like reins.
\par \lquote Ready?\rquote  he whispered to Hermione. \lquote You\rquote d better hold on to me \endash \rquote 
\par He nudged Buckbeak\rquote s sides with his heels.
\par Buckbeak soared straight into the dark air. Harry gripped his flanks with his knees, feeling the great wings rising powerfully beneath them. Hermione was holding Harry very tightly around the waist; he could hear her muttering, \lquote Oh, no \endash 
 I don\rquote t like this \endash  oh, I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196 really }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196 don\rquote t like this \endash 
\rquote 
\par Harry urged Buckbeak forwards. They were gliding quietly towards the upper floors of the castle ... Harry pulled hard on the left-hand side of the rope, and Buckbeak turned. Harry was trying to count the windows flashing past \endash 
\par \lquote Whoa!\rquote  he said, pulling backwards as hard as he could.
\par Buckbeak slowed down and they found themselves at a stop, unless you counted the fact that they kept rising up and down several feet as he beat his wings to remain airborne.
\par \lquote He\rquote s there!\rquote  Harry said, spotting Sirius as they rose up beside the window. He reached out, and as Buckbeak\rquote s wings fell, was able to tap sharply on the glass.
\par Black looked up. Harry saw his jaw drop. He leapt from his chair, hurried to the window and tried to open it, but it was locked.
\par \lquote Stand back!\rquote  Hermione called to him, and she took out her wand, still gripping the back of Harry\rquote s robes with her left hand.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196 \lquote Alohomora!\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196 
\par The window sprang open.
\par \lquote How \endash  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196 how}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af37 \ltrch\fcs0 \f37\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid2125196  \endash ?\rquote 
 said Black weakly, staring at the Hippogriff.
\par \lquote Get on \endash  there\rquote s not much time,\rquote  said Harry, gripping Buckbeak firmly on either side of his sleek neck to hold him steady. \lquote You\rquote ve got to get out of here \endash  the Dementors are coming. Macnair\rquote 
s gone to get them.\rquote 
\par Black placed a hand on either side of the window-frame and heaved his head and shoulders out of it. It was very lucky he was so thin. In seconds, he had managed to fling one leg over Buckbeak\rquote 
s back, and pull himself onto the Hippogriff behind Hermione.
\par \lquote OK, Buckbeak, up!\rquote  said Harry, shaking the rope. \lquote Up to the tower \endash  come on!\rquote 
\par The Hippogriff gave one sweep of its mighty wings and they were soaring upwards again, high as the top of the West Tower. Buckbeak landed with a clatter on the battlements and Harry and Hermione slid off him at once.
\par \lquote Sirius, you\rquote d better go, quick,\rquote  Harry panted. \lquote They\rquote ll reach Flitwick\rquote s office any moment, they\rquote ll find out you\rquote ve gone.\rquote 
\par Buckbeak pawed the ground, tossing his sharp head.
\par \lquote What happened to the other boy? Ron?\rquote  said Sirius urgently.
\par \lquote He\rquote s going to be OK \endash  he\rquote s still out of it, but Madam Pomfrey says she\rquote ll be able to make him better. Quick \endash  go!\rquote 
\par But Black was still staring down at Harry.
\par \lquote How can I ever thank \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote GO!\rquote  Harry and Hermione shouted together.
\par Black wheeled Buckbeak around, facing the open sky.
\par \lquote We\rquote ll see each other again,\rquote  he said. \lquote You are \endash  truly your father\rquote s son, Harry ...\rquote 
\par He squeezed Buckbeak\rquote 
s sides with his heels. Harry and Hermione jumped back as the enormous wings rose once more ... the Hippogriff took off into the air ... he and his rider became smaller and smaller as Harry gazed after them ... then a cloud drifted 
across the moon ... they were gone.
